Zambia prepares to expel british writer suspected of insulting his president
( Agence france - presse , Lusaka , 5th ) - Sabiya interior minister Sika Pawasha said that Sabiya had ordered british writer Clark to leave the country within 24 hours on the grounds that Clark " insulted " Sabiya president Mwanawasa in a weekly column in the popular newspaper post ( post ) .
Sikapavasha told a group of Mwanawasa supporters who marched to the interior ministry to demand Clark 's expulsion that " Clark will have to leave the country within 24 hours . "
I want to announce to the whole country that we have taken action . "
however , Clark said in an interview with afp that he had not received any notification .
Clark said : " I had no idea that an expulsion order had been issued . "
Mumba , permanent secretary of the ministry of the interior , said earlier that he had advised the interior minister to issue a eviction order .
Mumba said : " when someone insults a country 's president , it is tantamount to insulting the people he represents . he should go back and start writing articles about his own people . "
Clark has lived in Zambia for many years and is married to a prominent women 's rights activist .
Mumbe , editor of the post , said he was personally responsible for the article published last Thursday and urged the government of Zambia to point the finger at him rather than Clark .
Zambia has in the past expelled foreigners suspected of insulting the president or the head of government .
Koizumi vows to continue economic reform this year
( Agence france - presse , Tokyo , 5th ) - Japanese prime minister Junichiro Koizumi vowed at a press conference held on the first working day after the new year holiday that economic reform will continue this year . he said : " although the economic situation is still difficult , we can finally see signs of recovery . "
Koizumi stressed : " I will closely adhere to the reform policy and continue to push forward the reform .
continued reform efforts will promote economic recovery . &quot;
Koizumi said he would focus in particular on congressional deliberations on privatizing postal services this year .
" we will finally take action on privatizing the postal service , which is the main axis of economic reform , " he said .
Koizumi added that he hopes to present the bill to congress early next year .
Koizumi has pledged to fully privatize the postal service sector with 280,000 employees in 2007 .
Japan 's postal service sector is regarded as the world 's largest bank with 355 trillion yen ( $ 3.3 trillion ) of savings and insurance funds administered by it .
however , this large - scale plan still faces strong opposition from conservative congressmen .
the scheme began when Koizumi assumed the post of minister in 1993 .
analysts pointed out that the Japanese economy is expected to maintain steady growth of about 2 percent this year , but Japanese people may still be worried about further wage cuts and layoffs .
Japan 's unemployment rate is still above 5 percent while many companies continue to consolidate to ensure profits .
the United States begins photographing and fingerprinting inbound foreign travellers
( Agence france - presse , washington , 5 th ) - at a time when Singapore , home to asia 's largest airport , supports the deployment of additional air armed police on board flights to deal with terrorist threats , the united states began taking new measures to take photographs and retain fingerprints of incoming foreign passengers today .
Washington 's intensified efforts to check the timing of incoming foreign passengers coincided with the recent surge in global flight safety concerns , which have led to the temporary cancellation of several us flights in the past week .
the new measures only apply to foreign visitors who require visas to enter the united states , which is expected to reach 23 million this year .
the department of homeland security , which is responsible for implementing the " us - VISIT " program , pointed out that citizens of 28 countries , mostly in europe , can be exempted from the aforementioned procedure .
immigration groups criticized the plan as a violation of civil liberties and a step towards creating a surveillance society , and homeland security minister Reggie strongly defended the plan .
in an interview with the national broadcasting corporation ( NBC ) , Ridge said , " one of the first duties of any government is to ensure border security . we are doing the best we can to promote this plan . I think it is not reckless at all . in fact , it only takes about 15 seconds . obviously no one will care . "
up to five years from now , both land , sea and air entry points will be ready for photographing and fingerprinting .
all United States visas and passports will eventually be included in &quot; biometric markers , &quot; including photographs and fingerprints .
prior to the implementation of the aforesaid plan , the united states raised the alert level against the threat of terrorist attacks across the united states in december last year .
US , north korea take tough stance six - nation talks may be postponed until mid - year
( Agence france - presse , Seoul , 6th ) - south korea said today that due to the tough stance of north korea and the united states , a new round of six - nation nuclear talks may be postponed until the middle of the year .
" I hope the talks will be held in the first half of this year at the latest , " south Korean foreign minister Yoon young - Kwan told reporters when he went to attend a cabinet meeting in the blue house .
Yin Yongkuan made the remarks after washington rejected Pyongyang 's latest request for a major concession in exchange for a nuclear freeze and said the two sides still needed to resolve their serious differences before the nuclear talks .
Yin yongkuan said : the timing of the six participating countries has effectively ruled out the possibility of resuming the six - nation talks in january .
however , he did not provide any clues as to why the new round of talks might be postponed to june or beyond .
Russian deputy foreign minister Rosyukov attributed this to the tough stance of the united states and north korea .
he participated in the first round of six - nation talks held in beijing last august .
after meeting with senior Chinese officials yesterday , Rosyukov told Interfax that &quot; the reasons are the same as in the past - lack of mutual trust and harsh demands from both sides . &quot;
after north korea reiterated its demand for the united states to promise concessions before the new round of six - nation talks , yin yongkuan raised the possibility that the talks would be postponed for a long time .
Washington accused Pyongyang of setting preconditions for a new round of six - nation talks .
the United States is seeking a commitment from North Korea to dismantle its nuclear weapons program .
North korea said it would freeze nuclear facilities if washington lifted economic sanctions against Pyongyang and resumed energy aid .
in the past , north korea also insisted on signing a non - aggression treaty with the united states .
South asia summit concludes with thawing of indian - Pakistani relations
( Agence france - presse , Islamabad , 6 th ) - the south asia summit concluded today . during the summit , india and Pakistan , two hostile nuclear powers , completed breakthrough talks and the participating countries signed a free trade agreement , which is of epoch - making significance to the south asia region .
at the closing session of the 12th south Asian regional cooperation association ( SAARC ) summit , bangladesh prime minister Ms. Gia pointed out : " this summit is an important watershed in strengthening regional cooperation in south asia . "
Indian prime minister Vajpayee and Pakistani president Pervez Musharraf held their first talks since a nuclear war nearly broke out between the two countries in 2002 on the sidelines of the summit meeting yesterday .
the hostility between the two major powers of the south Asian association for regional cooperation has hindered regional development , and leaders of the participating countries are encouraged by the momentum for peace clearly brought about by the historic talks between india and Pakistan .
Pakistani military analyst ma shude told afp : " I think there has been a definite change in the position of india and Pakistan and the two countries are moving forward in the peace process . "
when officially announcing the conclusion of the summit , Pakistani prime minister Jamali praised the important agreements on anti - terrorism , alleviating poverty , and establishing a regional free trade zone from 2006 .
he also praised the summit as " injecting new vitality into regional cooperation . "
the heads of state and foreign ministers of bangladesh , bhutan , india , Maldivif , Nepal , Pakistan , and Sri lanka signed the south asia free trade area ( SAFTA ) agreement , the social charter , the anti-poverty plan , the anti-terrorism agreement , and the " Islamabad declaration " at the summit .
