the united states plans to release hundreds of Iraqi prisoners
( Agence france - presse , Baghdad ) - iraq 's interim chief executive Bremer , appointed by the us government , announced in a policy speech today that the us - led occupation alliance will release 100 Iraqi prisoners on the 8th and that hundreds more will be restored to freedom in the coming weeks .
Bremmer , accompanied by Iraqi interim governing council chairman Pachachi , also revealed a new reward scheme of up to 200,000 us dollars for assisting the authorities in arresting each of the other priority offenders .
Pachachi praised the aforesaid measures taken by the occupation alliance and said they were the result of strong lobbying by the ruling consultative council .
Pachachi told reporters : &quot; the governing council has long been working to spread a spirit of reconciliation among the Iraqi people . in order to achieve this goal , we ask the coalition to review the issue of prisoners . &quot;
a spokesman for the occupation alliance , who declined to be named , said later that a total of 506 prisoners were expected to be released in the coming weeks .
Bremer told reporters in his short speech : " the alliance will release the first batch of 100 prisoners tomorrow . "
Bremer 's conciliatory gesture comes at a time when the occupation alliance is trying to appease the accumulated resentment of Saddam Hussein 's muslim Sunni society .
Saddam Hussein was captured alive by the us military eight months after fleeing .
Bremer said : " tyrant Saddam Hussein has become a prisoner . most of his pawns have either been killed or arrested . the time has come for reconciliation . "
the conditions of release are that the prisoner &quot; must renounce violence &quot; and find witnesses , such as community figures or religious and tribal leaders , who bear the responsibility for the good behaviour of the released person .
Bremer pointed out that none of those to be released were directly involved in violent incidents or other deadly attacks against the us military , nor in torture or crimes against humanity .
Bremer said those who are about to be released &quot; made mistakes and have come to their senses . &quot; &quot; we are prepared to give some of them a chance to make a fresh start . &quot;
who experts visit Guangzhou to investigate the source of SARS
( Agence france - presse , Guangzhou , 10th ) - the world health organization ( who ) today launched its second investigation operation this year in response to another case of severe acute respiratory syndrome ( SARS ) in southern china .
the who has previously taken action to investigate the first confirmed case of SARS in the mainland in six months .
a who expert team and chinese health authorities conducted a surprise inspection of a seafood and game restaurant in Guangzhou city in an attempt to identify the source of one confirmed case of SARS and another suspected case .
who spokesman Wadia said in Guangzhou , " this trip starts with a review of the information we collected last time ... we will try to combine the pieces of information together . "
at the same time , the chinese government authorities have appealed to the public to put out rodents and other harmful animals that may carry the SARS virus .
health officials targeted the seafood restaurant , a 24 - hour restaurant in the heart of Guangzhou 's old city , where a 20 - year - old waitress was officially diagnosed as a suspected case of SARS late Wednesday .
who expert Brightman said , &quot; We have examined very carefully the possible environmental problems in the restaurant and will investigate further . &quot;
he said : " we talked with the staff of the restaurant and learned about the working methods inside the restaurant . we then visited the place where the food was cooked . environmental experts will continue this work . "
Brightman said it was too early to determine the cause of the disease because experts still had to sort out the research materials .
US openly supports construction of international thermonuclear reactor in japan
( Agence france - presse , Tokyo , 10th ) - the united states publicly supports for the first time the choice of building a multi - billion - dollar " international thermonuclear experimental reactor " ( ITER ) in Aomori prefecture , japan , instead of the french town of Cadarache , and claims that japan can provide superior construction sites .
the ITER is planned to be built in Cardalas , france , or six villages in Aomori prefecture , northern japan .
the project aims to provide an experimental site for simulating solar nuclear fusion , which has been hailed as the cleanest , safest and inexhaustible source of energy in the future .
however , it is generally expected that the aforementioned project will not be able to produce electricity before the year of 2 = 5 = years .
US Secretary of Energy Abraham said at a gathering of Japanese business leaders during his visit to Tokyo , &quot; I am honored to say today that the United States strongly supports the construction of an international thermonuclear experimental reactor in Japan . &quot;
from a technical point of view , you can provide superior sites . "
Abraham said , " the location of the six villages is very suitable for accommodating the huge materials needed for the international thermonuclear experimental reaction . your well - known technology and engineering skills are widely admired around the world . in addition , the local community has clearly welcomed the project and striven to win the selection of the six villages . "
a spokesman for the us embassy in Tokyo confirmed that this was the first time that washington authorities publicly expressed support for japan 's bid to build an international thermonuclear experimental reactor in japan .
an official from the Japanese ministry of education , culture , sports , science and technology said : " we are deeply encouraged by Abraham 's remarks .
" we will continue to work hand in hand with other countries to enable the ITER to be built in six villages . "
