Japan sets 10 - year target for balanced budget
( Agence france - presse , Tokyo , 16th ) - Japanese finance minister sadakazu tanigaki said today that he is confident that the world 's second largest economy will be able to extricate itself from a " fiscal crisis " and straighten out its finances within 10 years .
Mr tanigaki said the combined deficit between the central and local governments amounted to 5 percent of japan 's gross domestic product ( gdp ) and could be eliminated within 10 years if it were reduced by an average of 0.5 percent annually .
he told a group of reporters : " Japan 's fiscal situation is still in crisis .
" in terms of ( financial ) flows and reserves , our position is the worst among the major industrialized countries . "
Japan has formally set a target of turning the " original deficit " into " original surplus " for the year ending in march 2014 - for the first time in more than 20 years , multi - level fiscal balance will be achieved .
this is the first time that the government led by prime minister Junichiro Koizumi has given japan a clear goal of regaining an " original surplus . " under such circumstances , taxes exceed expenditures excluding debt-servicing expenses .
the last time japan recorded such a surplus was in the year before march 1992 , ending six consecutive years of surplus .
