the continuous decline of labor force is bound to hit economic production in the eu and japan .
( Agence france - presse , Davos , Switzerland , 19th ) - a research report published today by the world economic forum ( WEF ) and consulting firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide pointed out that due to the shrinking labor force , the proportion of european union output value in the global economic output value will be nearly halved by the end of the year .
in contrast , abundant labor in developing countries such as india and china should help boost economic growth .
" labor force growth and productivity will determine economic output .
in countries with large labor shortages , the supply of goods and services may not meet the demand and standard of living . "
the report , entitled &quot; Living Happier : the Economic Impact of an Aging Society , &quot; points out that due to the increase in human longevity due to advances in medical care , the increasing number of retirees , especially in developed countries , is bound to have a direct impact on economic production compared with the labor force .
a statement issued in response to the research report pointed out : " assuming that the current demographic and economic trends remain unchanged , the proportion of the european union in the global gross economic product will be reduced from the current 18 percent to 10 percent by the end of the second half of the year . "
the statement also warned that " japan 's share will shrink from 8 percent to 4 percent . "
