China takes measures to prevent tajikistan from entering the country with foot-and-mouth disease
Xinhua news agency , beijing , january 15 ( reporter du yu ) - the ministry of agriculture and the state general administration of quality supervision , inspection and quarantine recently issued a joint announcement banning the direct or indirect import of cloven - hoofed animals and their products from tajikistan , and returning or destroying all imported cloven - hoofed animals to china 's ports .
according to the world organization for animal health , three cases of foot-and-mouth disease type a have occurred in tajikistan recently .
in order to protect the safety of china 's animal husbandry , the ministry of agriculture and the state administration of quality supervision , inspection and quarantine also issued a circular banning the import of cloven - hoofed animals and their products from tajikistan by mail or by passengers .
if found , they will be returned or destroyed .
all ships , planes , trains , and other means of transport passing through china or stopping in china shall be sealed and disposed of if they find any birds or their products coming from the ROK , and all their waste and garbage shall be treated harmlessly under the supervision of the entry - exit inspection and quarantine organ , and shall not be discarded without authorization .
the circular demands that all smuggled cloven - hoofed animals and their products from tajikistan intercepted by customs and border defense departments be destroyed under the supervision of entry - exit inspection and quarantine organs .
( international ) airbus exceeds Boeing for the first time last year
Xinhua news agency report of january 15th from Paris ( by staff reporter Xu zhenqiang ) - the european airbus company said in a communique on the 15th that it had delivered 305 aircraft in 2003 , exceeding its original forecast of 300 , leading its competitor Boeing in the world for the first time .
Airbus delivered slightly more planes last year than 303 planes in 2002 .
the company predicts that the market will remain sluggish this year , so its aircraft volume is close to 300 pcs .
Boeing announced earlier this month that it had delivered 281 aircraft last year and is expected to deliver between 275 and 290 aircraft this year .
in 2003 , airbus 's global share of aircraft deliveries jumped to 52% , compared with 38% in 2001 and 44% in 2002 .
last year , airbus received 284 orders from customers , totaling 32.8 billion us dollars . excluding 30 cancelled orders , the actual number of orders reached 254 , accounting for 52 percent of the world 's total .
senior executives of european aerospace corporation , which owns 80% of airbus , said they do not expect the civil aircraft market to recover very quickly , but they hope airbus will maintain its current aircraft delivery level until 2005 .
